  "Prerequisites": "A basic familiarity with how public benefits or welfare systems operate, along with a willingness to explore how technology is used in government decision-making, is all that is needed to get started with this course.",
  "Learning objectives": "By the end of this course, you will be able to identify common sources of bias in AI-driven benefits and welfare eligibility systems, and explain how these biases can lead to unfair outcomes for vulnerable individuals and communities. You will also apply practical frameworks to assess and reduce fairness risks when working with or overseeing AI tools used in public sector welfare distribution.",
  "lessons": [
    {
      "lesson title": "AI in Benefits and Welfare Distribution",
      "order": 1,
      "Description": "This lesson explores how artificial intelligence is being used to support benefits and welfare distribution systems, and the potential risks that come with automating eligibility decisions. You will learn how AI tools can unintentionally reflect or even amplify existing biases, leading to unfair outcomes for vulnerable individuals and communities. We will look at real-world examples where automated decision-making has produced discriminatory results, and consider why this matters for public trust and social equity. By the end of this lesson, you will have a clearer understanding of the key fairness concerns surrounding AI in welfare systems, and what steps organisations can take to identify and reduce bias. No prior technical knowledge is required, as the focus is on practical awareness rather than complex algorithms.",
      "status": "draft",
