          "slidetitle": "Defining AI in Welfare Systems",
          "subtitle": "What AI means for welfare today",
          "slidecontent": "• AI in welfare refers to automated systems that assess, score, or flag claimants for benefits eligibility\n• These tools process large volumes of applications far faster than human caseworkers\n• Common examples include fraud detection algorithms, automated means-testing, and predictive risk scoring\n• Often invisible to claimants\n• The decisions these systems influence can directly affect whether someone receives housing support, disability benefits, or universal credit\n• Built on historical data, which means existing inequalities can be quietly baked in from the start"
